node.text: I am SO excited to announce the first ever Laurie Hernandez Champions Challenge this December!! Being Puerto Rican is something my family and I hold with pride and I couldn’t be more excited to bring this meet to San Juan. Go to Champions-Challenge.org for more info! (Link in bio) @lr_productions2020

node.text: Within everyone facing a mental health challenge lies the potential to be a champion. The hallmark of a Champion is the ability to learn and grow. That's why I'm teaming up on a new contest with @OneMindOrg that invites you to share your story to inspire healthy growth in others. Tell us about a life lesson you’ve learned through your (or a loved one’s) experience with mental health challenges that has made you stronger. Artwork, essay, photography, video — the medium is up to you. The first 100 entrants will take home a free prize package! All entrants have the chance to win incredible Finalist and Grand Prizes. Learn more at the link in bio.

node.text:
The last year has been crazy but I found this picture and it made me smile. My dad is amazing! He has supported me all the way, and he’s done it while managing his type 2 diabetes. That’s why I’m excited to partner with once- weekly @trulicity_us , a type 2 diabetes treatment. Trulicity is a type 2 diabetes treatment designed to be taken once a week—so it can help fit into a busy life! Plus, it starts acting in the body from the 1st dose. That first dose may start lowering blood sugar.

Learn about my partnership with Trulicity.com/teamusa. #TrulicityPartner

Laurie’s dad Tony Hernandez, who does not take Trulicity, inspired Laurie’s partnership with Trulicity to raise awareness of the health challenges faced by people living with type 2 diabetes.

SAFETY
Trulicity is a once-weekly injectable prescription medicine for adults with type 2 diabetes used to improve blood sugar along with diet and exercise and to reduce the risk of major cardiovascular events such as death, heart attack, or stroke for people who have heart disease or multiple risk factors. Trulicity isn’t for people with type 1 diabetes. Do not take Trulicity if you or a family member has had medullary thyroid cancer, if you’ve had Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndrome type 2, or if you are allergic to Trulicity. Stop Trulicity and call your doctor right away if you have a lump or swelling in your neck, severe pain in your stomach, or symptoms such as itching, rash, trouble breathing or changes in vision. Serious side effects may include pancreatitis, which can be fatal. Taking Trulicity with a sulfonylurea or insulin increases your risk for low blood sugar. Common side effects include nausea, diarrhea, vomiting, decreased appetite, indigestion, abdominal pain and fatigue. Some side effects can lead to dehydration, which may make existing kidney problems worse.

DG CON MSR SEP 2020

For Purpose & Safety Summary with Warnings see @trulicity_us highlights.

Information shared via direct or private message may be disclosed to Lilly and third parties in order to meet legal or regulatory requirements.

Guys, I did a commercial...with my DAD! 🎬🎥🌟We partnered up with the folks @trulicity_us to show the true power of healthy choices when it comes to the daily management of his type 2 diabetes... Check it out at Trulicity.com/teamusa #Trulicity #TokyoOlympics #TrulicityPartner #type2diabetes
 
Laurie’s dad Tony Hernandez, who does not take Trulicity, inspired Laurie’s partnership with Trulicity to raise awareness of the health challenges faced by people living with type 2 diabetes.
 
SAFETY:
Trulicity is a once-weekly injectable prescription medicine for adults with type 2 diabetes used to improve blood sugar along with diet and exercise and to reduce the risk of major cardiovascular events such as death, heart attack, or stroke for people who have heart disease or multiple risk factors. Trulicity isn’t for people with type 1 diabetes. Do not take Trulicity if you or a family member has had medullary thyroid cancer, if you’ve had Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia syndrome type 2, or if you are allergic to Trulicity. Stop Trulicity and call your doctor right away if you have a lump or swelling in your neck, severe pain in your stomach, or symptoms such as itching, rash, trouble breathing or changes in vision. Serious side effects may include pancreatitis, which can be fatal. Taking Trulicity with a sulfonylurea or insulin increases your risk for low blood sugar. Common side effects include nausea, diarrhea, vomiting, decreased appetite, indigestion, abdominal pain and fatigue. Some side effects can lead to dehydration, which may make existing kidney problems worse.
 
For Purpose & Safety Summary with Warnings see @trulicity_us highlights.
 
DG CON MSR SEP 2020
 
Information shared via direct or private message may be disclosed to Lilly and third parties in order to meet legal or regulatory requirements.
